Rules should be medically workable and consistently applied: protect privacy, ensure safe access and clinician discretion in emergencies, and include clearly defined exceptions for serious threats to health and pregnancies arising from violence, while avoiding punitive enforcement that deters care. Any legal framework should be paired with broad, noncoercive prevention and family supports—contraception, accurate education, prenatal/postpartum care, and economic help—so fewer people face unwanted pregnancies and more can choose parenting or adoption without hardship.
